article.description: Behind 24 points from Sam Cassell, 23 from Ray Allen and 22 from Glenn Robinson, the Milwaukee Bucks routed the Toronto Raptors 105-89 Tuesday night.
article.headline: Bucks help themselves in heated East race

images.name: Allen_Ray 020416 inline
images.caption: The Bucks' Ray Allen shoots over the Raptors' Keon Clark.

article.linkText: Bucks spoil Raptors bid to clinch playoff spot
article.story:
MILWAUKEE (AP) -- The "Big Three" finally lived up to their billing -- and just in time. Behind 24 points from a gimpy Sam Cassell, 23 from Ray Allen and 22 from Glenn Robinson, the Milwaukee Bucks routed the Toronto Raptors 105-89 Tuesday night. It was the first time in 25 games that the trio surpassed 20 points apiece. "It's been a while," said Allen, who suggested that for the first time in months coach George Karl could concentrate on coaching and not on who's hurt, who's hot and who's not meshing with whom. "He just sat there and drew up plays for all of us." Anthony Mason chipped in 18 points for the Bucks, who inched closer to a playoff berth while preventing the Raptors from clinching a postseason spot. "We've got one more," Karl said. "There's not a lot of celebration tonight. There's got to be preparation and rest." The Bucks, Raptors and Indiana Pacers are all 41-40 and fighting for the final two playoff berths heading into Wednesday night's season finales. Milwaukee owns the tiebreaker over both Toronto and Indiana, which beat Cleveland on Tuesday night. "It's amazing," Raptors coach Lenny Wilkens said. "You play 81 games and it comes down to the 82nd game. We have our opportunity tomorrow night and we need to be ready." Toronto finishes the regular season at home against the Cavaliers, with the Raptors having won six straight at the Air Canada Center. Indiana is at home against Philadelphia, and Milwaukee, which has lost 11 straight on the road, visits Detroit. "They both win and we lose, we're out," Karl said. "And they're both playing on their homecourt and we're going to be on the road." The Bucks have spent the last two months in a self-inflicted nose dive thanks to injuries, an inconsistent offense and festering infighting. Robinson said he doesn't care what the other teams do because "if we win, we control our own destination." Despite 21 points each from Keon Clark and Morris Peterson, Toronto lost for just the second time in 13 games since All-Star Vince Carter went down for the season with a knee injury. Jerome Williams said the Raptors, who lost 17 of 18 at one point, are confident they can stay hot should they clinch a playoff spot. "Tomorrow we have the opportunity to prove what we set out to prove, that you can't count us out," he said. "Tomorrow we have that opportunity to put all the critics to rest." Cassell reinjured his left big toe, which has bothered him all year, when he was stepped on by Alvin Williams just 10 seconds into the second half. He writhed in pain for three minutes before limping to the bench. But he returned late in the quarter and had a three-point play that gave Milwaukee, which trailed by 12 in the first half and 58-55 at halftime, a 77-70 lead. Karl said he intended to play Cassell for a bit to give Greg Anthony a rest, "but then he kept making shots." Cassell got hurt when he cut off Williams while going for the ball. "I got kicked and stepped on all at once," Cassell said. "It was just a matter of me letting my toe stop throbbing for a minute. I thought I'd be back in the fourth quarter. I will go to the hospital tonight and get X-rays and see what's going on with it." Cassell promised to play Wednesday night against the Pistons. "We've got a game to win," he said. "It's painful. But I'm going to do what I've got to do. I don't know how I'm going to do it." Cassell's was the latest in a series of scares for the Bucks, who have been riddled all season by injuries that have prevented them from reaching the heights many expected after they won the Central Division a year ago. "The combination of Sam on the floor and watching Mason shoot free throws have been very painful at times," Karl said, taking advantage of a rare light moment to rib Mason for his annoying hitch in his foul shots. The Raptors made their first 17 free throws but the Bucks didn't let them get to the line in the fourth quarter, committing just one foul as they outscored Toronto 26-15 to win going away. "If we play this hard and with this much intensity tomorrow night we'll come away with a win," Cassell said. The Raptors didn't dwell on the loss. "We feel good about having another opportunity," forward Antonio Davis said. "When you go through what we have gone through and it comes down to one game, what can you say? You have to be pleased. "I'm just hoping that this game didn't drain us." Game notes
Bucks G Michael Redd was activated from the injured list but did not play. He missed 11 games with a sprained ligament in his left knee. ... Bucks F Jason Caffey underwent surgery in Atlanta on Tuesday to remove bone spurs from his right ankle. ... The Raptors are 2-12 at the Bradley Center and 8-20 overall against Milwaukee. ... Cassell surpassed 9,000 career points.
